##################################################################################################
#
# a-rules package for association rules
# Association -> It investigates whether two products are being purchased together, and whether 
#                the purchase of one product increases the likelihood of purchasing the other.
# Support ->The proportion of times event A occurred is referred to as the support of A.
# Confidence -> It expresses our confidence that product B gets bought if A has been purchased.
# Lift -> Lift is defined as ratio Lift(A->B)=P(A and B)/P(A)P(B)
#
# Computational environment for mining association rules and frequent item sets
# we need to manipulate the data a bit before using arules
# we split the data in the vector x into groups defined in vector f
# in supermarket terminology, we think of users as shoppers and artists as items bought
#
#################################################################################################
library(arules)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'arules'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     %in%, abbreviate, write
library(Matrix)



# using split function to divide the data in the vector x into the groups defined by f.
# split into a list of users and the artist they listen to 
playlist = split(x=lastfm[,"artist"],f=lastfm$user)

# the first two listeners (1 and 3) listen to the following bands
playlist[1:2]
## $`1`
##  [1] red hot chili peppers   the black dahlia murder
##  [3] goldfrapp               dropkick murphys       
##  [5] le tigre                schandmaul             
##  [7] edguy                   jack johnson           
##  [9] eluveitie               the killers            
## [11] judas priest            rob zombie             
## [13] john mayer              the who                
## [15] guano apes              the rolling stones     
## 1004 Levels: ...and you will know us by the trail of dead [unknown] ... zero 7
## 
## $`3`

##  [4] aphex twin          animal collective   atmosphere         
##  [7] joanna newsom       air                 portishead         
## [10] massive attack      broken social scene arcade fire

## [28] mf doom             the books          
## 1004 Levels: ...and you will know us by the trail of dead [unknown] ... zero 7
# an artist may be mentioned by the same user more than once
# it is important to remove artist duplicates before creating
# the incidence matrix
playlist = lapply(playlist,unique) ## remove artist duplicates

## view this as a list of "transactions"
## transactions is a data class defined in arules
playlist = as(playlist,"transactions")
playlist[1:10]
## transactions in sparse format with
##  10 transactions (rows) and
##  1004 items (columns)
# lists the support of the 1,004 bands
# number of times band is listed to on the playlist of 15,000 users
# computes relative frequency of artist mentioned by the 15,000 users
itemFrequency(playlist)

#import library
library(arules)
# data to be analyzed
data(AdultUCI)
# dim is used to retrieve or set the dimensions of an object.
dim(AdultUCI) # 48842 records and 15 columns/variables
## [1] 48842    15
#fetching first three rows and all 15 columns
AdultUCI[1:3,]
##   age        workclass fnlwgt education education-num     marital-status
## 1  39        State-gov  77516 Bachelors            13      Never-married
## 2  50 Self-emp-not-inc  83311 Bachelors            13 Married-civ-spouse
## 3  38          Private 215646   HS-grad             9           Divorced
##          occupation  relationship  race  sex capital-gain capital-loss
## 1      Adm-clerical Not-in-family White Male         2174            0
## 2   Exec-managerial       Husband White Male            0            0
## 3 Handlers-cleaners Not-in-family White Male            0            0
##   hours-per-week native-country income
## 1             40  United-States  small
## 2             13  United-States  small
## 3             40  United-States  small
#by assigning null columns fnlwgt & education-num gets removed
AdultUCI[["fnlwgt"]] = NULL
AdultUCI[["education-num"]] = NULL




#Updating age attribute of the data into their respective age-range groups. 
AdultUCI[["age"]] = ordered(cut(AdultUCI[["age"]], c(15, 25, 45, 65, 100)), labels = c("Young", "Middle-aged", "Senior", "Old"))

#Updating hours-per-week attribute of the data into their respective range groups. 
AdultUCI[["hours-per-week"]] = ordered(cut(AdultUCI[["hours-per-week"]], c(0, 25, 40, 60, 168)), labels = c("Part-time","Full-time", "Over-time", "Workaholic"))

#Values above 0 should be relables as high.
#if values below zero should relabled as None, Values = 0 should be relables as low
AdultUCI[["capital-gain"]] = ordered(cut(AdultUCI[["capital-gain"]], c(-Inf, 0, median(AdultUCI[["capital-gain"]][AdultUCI[["capital-gain"]] > 0]), Inf)),labels = c("None", "Low", "High"))

#Updating capital-loss attribute of the data into their respective range groups. 
#Values above 0 should be relables as high.
AdultUCI[[ "capital-loss"]] = ordered(cut(AdultUCI[["capital-loss"]], c(-Inf, 0, median(AdultUCI[["capital-loss"]][AdultUCI[[ "capital-loss"]] > 0]), Inf)), labels = c("None", "Low", "High"))
